]]\n", "name_user": "98.151.151.84", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Off-the-grid"}
{"title_page": "David Ross (baseball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=David Ross\n|image=David Ross on June 30, 2016.jpg\n|image_size=270px\n|caption=Ross with the Chicago Cubs\n|team=Chicago Cubs\n|number=3\n|position=[[Catcher]] / [[Manager (baseball)|Manager]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1977|3|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Bainbridge, Georgia]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=June 29\n|debutyear=2002\n|debutteam=Los Angeles Dodgers\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 1\n|finalyear=2016\n|finalteam=Chicago Cubs\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.229\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=106\n|stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=314\n|teams= \n'''As player'''\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2002}}\u2013{{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|2005}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2005}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Atlanta Braves]] ({{mlby|2009}}\u2013{{mlby|2012}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2014}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2015}}\u2013{{mlby|2016}})\n'''As manager'''\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2020}}\u2013present)\n|highlights= \n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2013}}, {{wsy|2016}})\n}}\n\n'''David Wade Ross''' (born March 19, 1977) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[manager (baseball)|manager]] and former [[catcher]] for the [[Chicago Cubs]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He played for 14 years in MLB.\n\nRoss played [[college baseball]] for [[Auburn University]] and the [[University of Florida]] and participated in two [[College World Series]].  He started his major league career playing for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in 2002 and also played for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], [[San Diego Padres]], [[Cincinnati Reds]], [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Atlanta Braves]], and [[Chicago Cubs]]. Ross won the World Series with the [[Boston Red Sox]] in [[2013 Boston Red Sox season|2013]] and the [[Chicago Cubs]] in [[2016 Chicago Cubs season|2016]]. The Cubs named him their manager prior to the [[2020 Chicago Cubs season|2020 season]].\n\n==Early years==\nRoss was born in [[Bainbridge, Georgia]] in 1977, but was raised in Tallahassee, Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nesn.com/2014/05/david-ross-parents-crossed-state-lines-to-give-birth-to-red-sox-catcher/|title=David Ross' Parents Crossed State Lines To Give Birth To Red Sox Catcher|date=2014-05-01|work=NESN.com|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en-US}}</ref> He was born into a family of athletes - his father, David Ross, Sr., played in a men's softball league, and his mother, Jackie, played basketball. Ross's uncles were both football players in college.<ref name=\"m.mlb.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/183981732/david-ross-retirement-means-more-family-time/|title=David Ross' retirement means more family time|website=Major League Baseball|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-06}}</ref>  He attended [[Florida State University]]'s [[laboratory school]], [[Florida State University School|Florida High School]], in [[Tallahassee, Florida]], where he played high school baseball for the Florida High School Demons.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/03/sports/baseball/david-ross-chicago-cubs-game-7.html?_r=0\n|title=David Ross, Oldest Player in World Series, Ends Career in Climactic Game 7\n|author=David Waldstein\n|date=3 November 2016\n|newspaper=New York Times\n}}</ref> Ross was the first of five children; he has an older sister, Shannon, and a younger sister, Nikki.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tallahassee.com/story/sports/2016/11/03/friends-family-david-ross-celebrate-achievement/93235368/|title=Friends, family of David Ross celebrate achievement|work=Tallahassee Democrat|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nRoss received an [[athletic scholarship]] to attend Auburn University in [[Auburn, Alabama]], where he played [[college baseball]] for the [[Auburn Tigers baseball]] team from 1996 to 1997. In 1996, he played [[collegiate summer baseball]] with the [[Brewster Whitecaps]] of the [[Cape Cod Baseball League]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://capecodbaseball.org.ismmedia.com/ISM3/std-content/repos/Top/2012website/archives/Current%20Year/All_Time_MLB_CCBL_Alumni.pdf |title=Major League Baseball Players From the Cape Cod League |publisher=capecodbaseball.org |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref> The defining moment of his college career came in the semifinal of the East Regional tournament during the [[1997 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament|1997 College World Series]] when he hit a walk-off 3 run home run against [[Florida State Seminoles baseball|Florida State]] to advance to the regional final. The Auburn Tigers would advance to the College World Series, getting knocked out in the 2nd round by [[Stanford Cardinal baseball|Stanford]]. He transferred to the University of Florida after the 1997 season, and played one additional season of college baseball for the [[Florida Gators baseball]] team in 1998.  Ross is one of the few players to have played in the [[College World Series]] with two different colleges, first with the Tigers in [[1997 College World Series|1997]], and then the Gators in [[1998 College World Series|1998]]. Ross decided to forgo his final season of [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) eligibility after his junior season with the Gators, when he was drafted by the Los Angeles Dodgers.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers===\nRoss was drafted in the 19th round of the 1995 amateur draft by the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], but did not sign and accepted a scholarship to attend Auburn University instead.  In 1998 the Dodgers drafted Ross again, this time in the 7th round.<ref name=nyt/>\n\nRoss made his MLB debut on June 29, 2002, striking out as a pinch hitter.  On September 2, 2002, with the Dodgers leading 18\u20130,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ARI/ARI200209020.shtml September 2, 2002 Los Angeles Dodgers at Arizona Diamondbacks Play by Play and Box Score \u2013 Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Diamondbacks put first baseman [[Mark Grace]] in to pitch after he volunteered, to rest the [[bullpen]]. Ross hit his 1st major league home run off Grace with two outs in the 9th inning, capping a 19-1 win. Ross's Dodger career was stalled, however, by the large number of catchers in the Dodger system.  [[Paul Lo Duca]] was the starting catcher through most of Ross's time in Los Angeles, and teammates like [[Brent Mayne]], [[Koyie Hill]], and [[Todd Hundley]] competed with him for playing time. Ross stayed with the team until 2004.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n===Pittsburgh Pirates / San Diego Padres===\nThe Dodgers sold Ross's contract to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] on March 30, 2005. After 40 games with the Pirates, he was traded to the [[San Diego Padres]] on July 28, 2005 for [[infielder]] [[J. J. Furmaniak]]. He played in 11 games with the Padres.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Cincinnati Reds===\n[[File:David Ross on May 11, 2008.jpg|280px|thumb|right|Ross playing for the [[2008 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati Reds in 2008]]]]\nThe Padres traded Ross to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] during [[spring training]] for the 2006 season. On January 15, 2006, Ross signed a two-year, $4.54&nbsp;million contract with the Reds.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nWhile Ross was most often used as the \"personal catcher\" for right-hander [[Bronson Arroyo]], whom the Reds received in a spring training trade with the [[Boston Red Sox]] for [[outfielder]] [[Wily Mo Pe\u00f1a]], the consensus among Reds fans was that Ross had proven himself deserving of being the number-one catcher due to his better offensive numbers and that one of the other Reds catchers, [[Jason LaRue]] or [[Javier Valent\u00edn]], should have been traded (possibly as part of a package deal) for a [[relief pitcher]]. LaRue was the one most frequently cited, but no deal was made by the July 31 trade deadline. Ostensibly, Ross was the number-one catcher.\n\nOn November 20, 2006, LaRue was traded to the [[Kansas City Royals]] for a player to be named later. Ross's 2007 season started with 4 hits in 38 [[at-bat]]s with no home runs and 17 [[strikeout]]s. On April 21, 2007, his slump hit rock bottom when with runners on first and second base, he grounded into a rare 5\u20134\u20133 [[triple play]] against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. Ross finished the 2007 season with a .203 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] and 17 home runs.  On August 10, 2008, Ross was designated for assignment and was released on August 18.\n\n===Boston Red Sox===\nRoss signed a minor-league contract with the [[Boston Red Sox]]<ref>{{cite news |title = Report: Sox sign catcher Ross to minor-league deal \n|date=August 21, 2008 |work=[[Boston Globe]] | author=Steve Silva |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2008/08/report_sox_sign.html |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> on August 22, 2008. He came up to the MLB club on August 29 and became a free agent after the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080829&content_id=3386053&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&partnerId=rss_mlb\n|title=Sox call up Ross, send Casey to DL|date=August 29, 2008 |publisher=[[MLB.com]] | author=Mark Remme | accessdate=August 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Atlanta Braves===\n[[File:David Ross 2012.jpg|260px|thumb|Ross with the [[2012 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves in 2012]]]]\nThe [[Atlanta Braves]] signed Ross to a two-year, $3 million deal on December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://atlanta.braves.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081205&content_id=3703974&vkey=news_atl&fext=.jsp&c_id=atl|title=Braves sign Ross to two-year deal|last=Bowman|first=Mark|accessdate=November 18, 2009|date=December 5, 2008 |publisher=[[MLB.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Ross hit .273 in 54 games. On July 27, 2010, he signed a two-year extension to stay with the Braves through 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/38432113/ns/sports-player_news/|title=Report: Ross, Braves reach two-year extension|last=Rosenthal|first=Ken|accessdate=February 9, 2016|date=July 27, 2010 |publisher=NBC Sports |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009125507/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/38432113/ns/sports-player_news/ |archivedate=October 9, 2012}}</ref> He managed to hit a career high .289 for the Braves in 59 games in 2010.\n\nRoss was the Atlanta Braves secondary catcher behind [[Brian McCann (baseball)|Brian McCann]] for his four seasons with the Braves. His hot start in the 2011 season (hitting .333 after starting 7 games, with 3 home runs) highlighted his strengths, as Ross has always been known as a strong defensive catcher (in 2009, he committed one [[Error (baseball)|error]] in 52 games). Ross hit the first ever home run in the [[2012 National League Wild Card Game|Wild Card Game]] when the new playoff format was introduced in 2012.\n\n===Boston Red Sox (second stint)===\n\n[[File:David Ross on April 3, 2014.jpg|thumb|Ross with the Red Sox in 2014]]\n\nRoss signed a two-year, $6.2 million deal on November 10, 2012, to return to the Red Sox as \"more than a backup but not a starter\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/boston-red-sox-catcher-david-ross-agree-to-two-year-deal-111012 |title=Red Sox, Ross agree to two-year deal |work=Fox Sports |first=Ken |last=Rosenthal |date=November 10, 2012}}</ref> behind primary catcher [[Jarrod Saltalamacchia]].\n\nRoss suffered two concussions during the 2013 season and spent over two months on the disabled list; however, his health returned and he played a key role in Boston's run to the [[2013 World Series|World Series championship]] over the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] that year, starting in four games during the series and driving in the game-winning run with an RBI double in Game 5. He was also behind the plate to catch the series-clinching out in Game 6 when [[Koji Uehara]] struck out [[Matt Carpenter (baseball)|Matt Carpenter]].\n\nIn 2014, Ross played as [[Jon Lester]]'s [[catcher#Personal catcher|personal catcher]].\n\n===Chicago Cubs===\nThe [[Chicago Cubs]] announced on December 23, 2014, that they had signed Ross to a two-year, $5 million contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/chi-catcher-david-ross-signs-deal-cubs-20141223-story.html|title=Catcher David Ross officially signs two-year deal with Cubs|work=Chicago Tribune|first=Paul|last=Sullivan|date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2015, in his first appearance as a pitcher in his professional baseball career, Ross recorded a perfect inning against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/123456158/chicago-cubs-catcher-david-ross-pitches-a-perfect-eighth-inning|title=Catcher Ross pitches a perfect eighth inning|work=MLB.com|first=Jim|last=Hoehn|date=May 9, 2015|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref> On July 26, he repeated the feat against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], then led off the next inning by hitting a home run off of [[H\u00e9ctor Neris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/138907200/david-ross-throws-perfect-9th-homers-for-cubs|title=Ross pitches perfect ninth, homers for Cubs|work=MLB.com|first=Greg|last=Garno|date=July 26, 2015|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2016, Ross caught his first no-hitter, against the Cincinnati Reds, his former team, with starting pitcher [[Jake Arrieta]]. Ross hit his 100th home run off of [[Adam Morgan (baseball)|Adam Morgan]] of the Philadelphia Phillies on May 27, 2016.\n\nRoss announced his plans to retire following the 2016 season, after playing 15 seasons in the major leagues. During [[2016 World Series#Game 7|Game 7 of the 2016 MLB World Series]], Ross hit a home run making him the oldest player to do so in World Series history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Alex|title=Former SEC star David Ross makes World Series history in final career game|url=https://www.seccountry.com/florida/former-sec-star-david-ross-makes-world-series-history-in-final-career-game|accessdate=November 2, 2016|work=SEC Country|date=November 2, 2016}}</ref> On January 14, 2017, the Cubs named Ross as a special assistant to baseball operations for the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cubs Name David Ross Special Assistant to Baseball Operations|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/sports/chicago-cubs-david-ross-special-assistant-to-baseball-410672575.html|website=www.nbcchicago.com|publisher=NBC Chicago|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Kansas Stars===\nFollowing his retirement from the MLB, Ross joined the [[Kansas Stars]], an independent baseball team made of former MLB stars who play an abbreviated tournament lasting a few weeks out of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wgntv.com/2017/07/10/former-cubs-catcher-david-ross-is-returning-to-diamond-for-the-kansas-stars/|title=Former Cubs catcher David Ross is returning to diamond \u2013 for the Kansas Stars|first=Larry|last=Hawley|publisher=[[WGN9]]|date=July 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\nThe Cubs named Ross a special assistant after his retirement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/sports/chicago-cubs-david-ross-special-assistant-to-baseball-410672575.html|title=Cubs Announce New Role for David Ross|work=NBC Chicago|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en}}</ref> [[ESPN]] hired Ross as a baseball [[color analyst]] in January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/18584009/former-chicago-cubs-catcher-david-ross-work-espn|title=Former Chicago Cubs catcher David Ross to be baseball analyst for ESPN|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nOn October 24, 2019, the Cubs hired Ross as their manager to replace [[Joe Maddon]], signing him to a three-year contract.<ref>https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/27909976/sources-cubs-hire-david-ross-manager</ref>\n\n===Managerial record===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular season !! colspan=\"4\"|Postseason\n|-\n!Games!!Won!!Lost!!Win %!!Finish!! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Result\n|-\n![[2020 Chicago Cubs season|CHC]]||[[2020 Chicago Cubs season|2020]]\n||-||-||-||{{Winning percentage||}}|| - || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||  \u2013\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total||-||-||-||{{Winning percentage||}}||||-|| - || {{Winning percentage||}} || \n|-\n|}\n\n==''Dancing with the Stars''==\nOn March 1, 2017, Ross was revealed as one of the contestants on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 24)|season 24]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' and was paired with professional dancer [[Lindsay Arnold]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/dancing-stars-2017-season-24-celebrity-cast-partners/story?id=45767534|title='Dancing With the Stars' 2017: Season 24 celebrity cast and partners revealed on 'GMA'|work=ABC News|accessdate=March 1, 2016|date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> Ross is the first professional baseball player ever to compete on the show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kubicek|first1=John|title='Dancing with the Stars' Recap: The Magical World of Disney Night John|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-live-bl-64236.aspx|website=www.buddytv.com|publisher=Buddy TV|accessdate=21 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418164127/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-live-bl-64236.aspx|archive-date=April 18, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite only having the sixth-highest scoring average, Ross and Arnold outlasted higher-scoring couples and ended up placing runner-up to winner [[Rashad Jennings]] and partner [[Emma Slater]].\n\n==Personal life==\nRoss is married to Hyla Ross. Together they have three children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/183981732/david-ross-retirement-means-more-family-time/|title=David Ross' retirement means more family time|website=Major League Baseball|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-02}}</ref> As of 2016, they resided in Tallahassee, Florida.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/183981732/david-ross-retirement-means-more-family-time/ |title = David Ross' retirement means more family time}}</ref>\n\nRoss is a Christian.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/david-ross.php |title = David Ross Speaker & Agent Info: Christian Speakers 360}}</ref>\n\nRoss has worked with several Chicago charities including Cradle to Crayons that benefits underprivileged Chicago youth.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nRoss worked with author [[Don Yaeger]], on a book titled '' Teammate: My Life in Baseball,'' which was published in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/cutfour/2016/12/14/211142650/david-ross-is-writing-a-book-about-his-career|title=David Ross is writing a book about his career and Game 7 of the World Series|website=Major League Baseball|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-06}}</ref>\n\nHe has made an appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]], '' along with some of his teammates, to celebrate the Cubs championship win.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/the-cubs-will-appear-on-this-weeks-episode-of-saturday-night-live/|title=The Cubs will appear on this week's episode of 'Saturday Night Live'|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en}}</ref> Ross has also made an appearance in the recent commercials for  \"The Bryzzo Souvenir Company\" as an intern trying to meet the standards and requests of his bosses, [[Kris Bryant]] and [[Anthony Rizzo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/david-ross-struggling-in-role-as-bryzzo-intern-in-new-clip-420107404.html|title=David Ross Struggles as 'Bryzzo' Intern in New Clip|work=NBC Chicago|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427125450/http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/david-ross-struggling-in-role-as-bryzzo-intern-in-new-clip-420107404.html|archivedate=April 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Biography}}\n* [[List of Auburn University people]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players with a home run in their final major league at bat]]\n* [[List of Florida Gators baseball players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|David Ross (baseball)|David Ross}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=424325|espn=5206|br=r/rossda01|fangraphs=1551|brm=ross--003dav|retro=R/Prossd001}}\n*{{twitter}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|''Dancing with the Stars'' (US)]] runner up | before= [[James Hinchcliffe]] & [[Sharna Burgess]] | years=Season 24<br>(Spring 2016 with [[Lindsay Arnold]]) |after=[[Lindsey Stirling]] & [[Mark Ballas]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{2013 Boston Red Sox}}\n{{2016 Chicago Cubs}}\n{{ESPN Major League Baseball}}\n{{Chicago Cubs roster navbox}}\n{{Chicago Cubs managers}}\n{{MLB managers by team}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ross, David}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Braves players]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers baseball players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Brewster Whitecaps players]]\n[[Category:Chattanooga Lookouts players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators baseball players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Suns players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas 51s players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Louisville Bats players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:People from Bainbridge, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Portland Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Portland Sea Dogs players]]\n[[Category:Rome Braves players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Missions players]]\n[[Category:San Bernardino Stampede players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Sarasota Reds players]]\n[[Category:Vero Beach Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Yakima Bears players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = David Ross\n| image       = David Ross on June 30, 2016.jpg\n| image_size  = 270\n| caption     = Ross with the Chicago Cubs in 2016\n| team        = Chicago Cubs\n| number      = 3\n| position    = [[Catcher]] / [[Manager (baseball)|Manager]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1977|3|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bainbridge, Georgia]]\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = June 29\n| debutyear   = 2002\n| debutteam   = Los Angeles Dodgers\n| finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate = October 1\n| finalyear = 2016\n| finalteam = Chicago Cubs\n| statleague = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .229\n| stat3label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat3value  = 106\n| stat4label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat4value  = 314\n| teams       = \n;As player\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2002}}\u2013{{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|2005}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2005}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Atlanta Braves]] ({{mlby|2009}}\u2013{{mlby|2012}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2014}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2015}}\u2013{{mlby|2016}})\n;As manager\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2020}}\u2013present)\n|awards= \n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2013}}, {{wsy|2016}})\n}}\n\n'''David Wade Ross''' (born March 19, 1977) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[manager (baseball)|manager]] and former [[catcher]] for the [[Chicago Cubs]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He played for 14 years in MLB.\n\nRoss played [[college baseball]] for [[Auburn University]] and the [[University of Florida]] and participated in two [[College World Series]].  He started his major league career playing for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in 2002 and also played for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], [[San Diego Padres]], [[Cincinnati Reds]], [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Atlanta Braves]], and [[Chicago Cubs]]. Ross won the World Series with the [[Boston Red Sox]] in [[2013 Boston Red Sox season|2013]] and the [[Chicago Cubs]] in [[2016 Chicago Cubs season|2016]]. The Cubs named him their manager prior to the [[2020 Chicago Cubs season|2020 season]].\n\n==Early years==\nRoss was born in [[Bainbridge, Georgia]] in 1977, but was raised in Tallahassee, Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nesn.com/2014/05/david-ross-parents-crossed-state-lines-to-give-birth-to-red-sox-catcher/|title=David Ross' Parents Crossed State Lines To Give Birth To Red Sox Catcher|date=2014-05-01|work=NESN.com|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en-US}}</ref> He was born into a family of athletes - his father, David Ross, Sr., played in a men's softball league, and his mother, Jackie, played basketball. Ross's uncles were both football players in college.<ref name=\"m.mlb.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/183981732/david-ross-retirement-means-more-family-time/|title=David Ross' retirement means more family time|website=Major League Baseball|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-06}}</ref>  He attended [[Florida State University]]'s [[laboratory school]], [[Florida State University School|Florida High School]], in [[Tallahassee, Florida]], where he played high school baseball for the Florida High School Demons.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/03/sports/baseball/david-ross-chicago-cubs-game-7.html?_r=0\n|title=David Ross, Oldest Player in World Series, Ends Career in Climactic Game 7\n|author=David Waldstein\n|date=3 November 2016\n|newspaper=New York Times\n}}</ref> Ross was the first of five children; he has an older sister, Shannon, and a younger sister, Nikki.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tallahassee.com/story/sports/2016/11/03/friends-family-david-ross-celebrate-achievement/93235368/|title=Friends, family of David Ross celebrate achievement|work=Tallahassee Democrat|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nRoss received an [[athletic scholarship]] to attend Auburn University in [[Auburn, Alabama]], where he played [[college baseball]] for the [[Auburn Tigers baseball]] team from 1996 to 1997. In 1996, he played [[collegiate summer baseball]] with the [[Brewster Whitecaps]] of the [[Cape Cod Baseball League]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://capecodbaseball.org.ismmedia.com/ISM3/std-content/repos/Top/2012website/archives/Current%20Year/All_Time_MLB_CCBL_Alumni.pdf |title=Major League Baseball Players From the Cape Cod League |publisher=capecodbaseball.org |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref> The defining moment of his college career came in the semifinal of the East Regional tournament during the [[1997 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament|1997 College World Series]] when he hit a walk-off 3 run home run against [[Florida State Seminoles baseball|Florida State]] to advance to the regional final. The Auburn Tigers would advance to the College World Series, getting knocked out in the 2nd round by [[Stanford Cardinal baseball|Stanford]]. He transferred to the University of Florida after the 1997 season, and played one additional season of college baseball for the [[Florida Gators baseball]] team in 1998.  Ross is one of the few players to have played in the [[College World Series]] with two different colleges, first with the Tigers in [[1997 College World Series|1997]], and then the Gators in [[1998 College World Series|1998]]. Ross decided to forgo his final season of [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) eligibility after his junior season with the Gators, when he was drafted by the Los Angeles Dodgers.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers===\nRoss was drafted in the 19th round of the 1995 amateur draft by the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], but did not sign and accepted a scholarship to attend Auburn University instead.  In 1998 the Dodgers drafted Ross again, this time in the 7th round.<ref name=nyt/>\n\nRoss made his MLB debut on June 29, 2002, striking out as a pinch hitter.  On September 2, 2002, with the Dodgers leading 18\u20130,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ARI/ARI200209020.shtml September 2, 2002 Los Angeles Dodgers at Arizona Diamondbacks Play by Play and Box Score \u2013 Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Diamondbacks put first baseman [[Mark Grace]] in to pitch after he volunteered, to rest the [[bullpen]]. Ross hit his 1st major league home run off Grace with two outs in the 9th inning, capping a 19-1 win. Ross's Dodger career was stalled, however, by the large number of catchers in the Dodger system.  [[Paul Lo Duca]] was the starting catcher through most of Ross's time in Los Angeles, and teammates like [[Brent Mayne]], [[Koyie Hill]], and [[Todd Hundley]] competed with him for playing time. Ross stayed with the team until 2004.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n===Pittsburgh Pirates / San Diego Padres===\nThe Dodgers sold Ross's contract to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] on March 30, 2005. After 40 games with the Pirates, he was traded to the [[San Diego Padres]] on July 28, 2005 for [[infielder]] [[J. J. Furmaniak]]. He played in 11 games with the Padres.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Cincinnati Reds===\n[[File:David Ross on May 11, 2008.jpg|280px|thumb|right|Ross playing for the [[2008 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati Reds in 2008]]]]\nThe Padres traded Ross to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] during [[spring training]] for the 2006 season. On January 15, 2006, Ross signed a two-year, $4.54&nbsp;million contract with the Reds.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nWhile Ross was most often used as the \"personal catcher\" for right-hander [[Bronson Arroyo]], whom the Reds received in a spring training trade with the [[Boston Red Sox]] for [[outfielder]] [[Wily Mo Pe\u00f1a]], the consensus among Reds fans was that Ross had proven himself deserving of being the number-one catcher due to his better offensive numbers and that one of the other Reds catchers, [[Jason LaRue]] or [[Javier Valent\u00edn]], should have been traded (possibly as part of a package deal) for a [[relief pitcher]]. LaRue was the one most frequently cited, but no deal was made by the July 31 trade deadline. Ostensibly, Ross was the number-one catcher.\n\nOn November 20, 2006, LaRue was traded to the [[Kansas City Royals]] for a player to be named later. Ross's 2007 season started with 4 hits in 38 [[at-bat]]s with no home runs and 17 [[strikeout]]s. On April 21, 2007, his slump hit rock bottom when with runners on first and second base, he grounded into a rare 5\u20134\u20133 [[triple play]] against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. Ross finished the 2007 season with a .203 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] and 17 home runs.  On August 10, 2008, Ross was designated for assignment and was released on August 18.\n\n===Boston Red Sox===\nRoss signed a minor-league contract with the [[Boston Red Sox]]<ref>{{cite news |title = Report: Sox sign catcher Ross to minor-league deal \n|date=August 21, 2008 |work=[[Boston Globe]] | author=Steve Silva |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2008/08/report_sox_sign.html |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> on August 22, 2008. He came up to the MLB club on August 29 and became a free agent after the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080829&content_id=3386053&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&partnerId=rss_mlb\n|title=Sox call up Ross, send Casey to DL|date=August 29, 2008 |publisher=[[MLB.com]] | author=Mark Remme | accessdate=August 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Atlanta Braves===\n[[File:David Ross 2012.jpg|260px|thumb|Ross with the [[2012 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves in 2012]]]]\nThe [[Atlanta Braves]] signed Ross to a two-year, $3 million deal on December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://atlanta.braves.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081205&content_id=3703974&vkey=news_atl&fext=.jsp&c_id=atl|title=Braves sign Ross to two-year deal|last=Bowman|first=Mark|accessdate=November 18, 2009|date=December 5, 2008 |publisher=[[MLB.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Ross hit .273 in 54 games. On July 27, 2010, he signed a two-year extension to stay with the Braves through 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/38432113/ns/sports-player_news/|title=Report: Ross, Braves reach two-year extension|last=Rosenthal|first=Ken|accessdate=February 9, 2016|date=July 27, 2010 |publisher=NBC Sports |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009125507/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/38432113/ns/sports-player_news/ |archivedate=October 9, 2012}}</ref> He managed to hit a career high .289 for the Braves in 59 games in 2010.\n\nRoss was the Atlanta Braves secondary catcher behind [[Brian McCann (baseball)|Brian McCann]] for his four seasons with the Braves. His hot start in the 2011 season (hitting .333 after starting 7 games, with 3 home runs) highlighted his strengths, as Ross has always been known as a strong defensive catcher (in 2009, he committed one [[Error (baseball)|error]] in 52 games). Ross hit the first ever home run in the [[2012 National League Wild Card Game|Wild Card Game]] when the new playoff format was introduced in 2012.\n\n===Boston Red Sox (second stint)===\n\n[[File:David Ross on April 3, 2014.jpg|thumb|Ross with the Red Sox in 2014]]\n\nRoss signed a two-year, $6.2 million deal on November 10, 2012, to return to the Red Sox as \"more than a backup but not a starter\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/boston-red-sox-catcher-david-ross-agree-to-two-year-deal-111012 |title=Red Sox, Ross agree to two-year deal |work=Fox Sports |first=Ken |last=Rosenthal |date=November 10, 2012}}</ref> behind primary catcher [[Jarrod Saltalamacchia]].\n\nRoss suffered two concussions during the 2013 season and spent over two months on the disabled list; however, his health returned and he played a key role in Boston's run to the [[2013 World Series|World Series championship]] over the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] that year, starting in four games during the series and driving in the game-winning run with an RBI double in Game 5. He was also behind the plate to catch the series-clinching out in Game 6 when [[Koji Uehara]] struck out [[Matt Carpenter (baseball)|Matt Carpenter]].\n\nIn 2014, Ross played as [[Jon Lester]]'s [[catcher#Personal catcher|personal catcher]].\n\n===Chicago Cubs===\nThe [[Chicago Cubs]] announced on December 23, 2014, that they had signed Ross to a two-year, $5 million contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/chi-catcher-david-ross-signs-deal-cubs-20141223-story.html|title=Catcher David Ross officially signs two-year deal with Cubs|work=Chicago Tribune|first=Paul|last=Sullivan|date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2015, in his first appearance as a pitcher in his professional baseball career, Ross recorded a perfect inning against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/123456158/chicago-cubs-catcher-david-ross-pitches-a-perfect-eighth-inning|title=Catcher Ross pitches a perfect eighth inning|work=MLB.com|first=Jim|last=Hoehn|date=May 9, 2015|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref> On July 26, he repeated the feat against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], then led off the next inning by hitting a home run off of [[H\u00e9ctor Neris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/138907200/david-ross-throws-perfect-9th-homers-for-cubs|title=Ross pitches perfect ninth, homers for Cubs|work=MLB.com|first=Greg|last=Garno|date=July 26, 2015|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2016, Ross caught his first no-hitter, against the Cincinnati Reds, his former team, with starting pitcher [[Jake Arrieta]]. Ross hit his 100th home run off of [[Adam Morgan (baseball)|Adam Morgan]] of the Philadelphia Phillies on May 27, 2016.\n\nRoss announced his plans to retire following the 2016 season, after playing 15 seasons in the major leagues. During [[2016 World Series#Game 7|Game 7 of the 2016 MLB World Series]], Ross hit a home run making him the oldest player to do so in World Series history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Alex|title=Former SEC star David Ross makes World Series history in final career game|url=https://www.seccountry.com/florida/former-sec-star-david-ross-makes-world-series-history-in-final-career-game|accessdate=November 2, 2016|work=SEC Country|date=November 2, 2016}}</ref> On January 14, 2017, the Cubs named Ross as a special assistant to baseball operations for the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cubs Name David Ross Special Assistant to Baseball Operations|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/sports/chicago-cubs-david-ross-special-assistant-to-baseball-410672575.html|website=www.nbcchicago.com|publisher=NBC Chicago|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Kansas Stars===\nFollowing his retirement from the MLB, Ross joined the [[Kansas Stars]], an independent baseball team made of former MLB stars who play an abbreviated tournament lasting a few weeks out of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wgntv.com/2017/07/10/former-cubs-catcher-david-ross-is-returning-to-diamond-for-the-kansas-stars/|title=Former Cubs catcher David Ross is returning to diamond \u2013 for the Kansas Stars|first=Larry|last=Hawley|publisher=[[WGN9]]|date=July 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\nThe Cubs named Ross a special assistant after his retirement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/sports/chicago-cubs-david-ross-special-assistant-to-baseball-410672575.html|title=Cubs Announce New Role for David Ross|work=NBC Chicago|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en}}</ref> [[ESPN]] hired Ross as a baseball [[color analyst]] in January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/18584009/former-chicago-cubs-catcher-david-ross-work-espn|title=Former Chicago Cubs catcher David Ross to be baseball analyst for ESPN|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nOn October 24, 2019, the Cubs hired Ross as their manager to replace [[Joe Maddon]], signing him to a three-year contract.<ref>https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/27909976/sources-cubs-hire-david-ross-manager</ref>\n\n===Managerial record===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular season !! colspan=\"4\"|Postseason\n|-\n!Games!!Won!!Lost!!Win %!!Finish!! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Result\n|-\n![[2020 Chicago Cubs season|CHC]]||[[2020 Chicago Cubs season|2020]]\n||-||-||-||{{Winning percentage||}}|| - || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||  \u2013\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total||-||-||-||{{Winning percentage||}}||||-|| - || {{Winning percentage||}} || \n|-\n|}\n\n==''Dancing with the Stars''==\nOn March 1, 2017, Ross was revealed as one of the contestants on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 24)|season 24]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' and was paired with professional dancer [[Lindsay Arnold]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/dancing-stars-2017-season-24-celebrity-cast-partners/story?id=45767534|title='Dancing With the Stars' 2017: Season 24 celebrity cast and partners revealed on 'GMA'|work=ABC News|accessdate=March 1, 2016|date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> Ross is the first professional baseball player ever to compete on the show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kubicek|first1=John|title='Dancing with the Stars' Recap: The Magical World of Disney Night John|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-live-bl-64236.aspx|website=www.buddytv.com|publisher=Buddy TV|accessdate=21 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418164127/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-live-bl-64236.aspx|archive-date=April 18, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite only having the sixth-highest scoring average, Ross and Arnold outlasted higher-scoring couples and ended up placing runner-up to winner [[Rashad Jennings]] and partner [[Emma Slater]].\n\n==Personal life==\nRoss is married to Hyla Ross. Together they have three children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/183981732/david-ross-retirement-means-more-family-time/|title=David Ross' retirement means more family time|website=Major League Baseball|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-02}}</ref> As of 2016, they resided in Tallahassee, Florida.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/183981732/david-ross-retirement-means-more-family-time/ |title = David Ross' retirement means more family time}}</ref>\n\nRoss is a Christian.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/david-ross.php |title = David Ross Speaker & Agent Info: Christian Speakers 360}}</ref>\n\nRoss has worked with several Chicago charities including Cradle to Crayons that benefits underprivileged Chicago youth.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nRoss worked with author [[Don Yaeger]], on a book titled '' Teammate: My Life in Baseball,'' which was published in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/cutfour/2016/12/14/211142650/david-ross-is-writing-a-book-about-his-career|title=David Ross is writing a book about his career and Game 7 of the World Series|website=Major League Baseball|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-06}}</ref>\n\nHe has made an appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]], '' along with some of his teammates, to celebrate the Cubs championship win.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/the-cubs-will-appear-on-this-weeks-episode-of-saturday-night-live/|title=The Cubs will appear on this week's episode of 'Saturday Night Live'|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en}}</ref> Ross has also made an appearance in the recent commercials for  \"The Bryzzo Souvenir Company\" as an intern trying to meet the standards and requests of his bosses, [[Kris Bryant]] and [[Anthony Rizzo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/david-ross-struggling-in-role-as-bryzzo-intern-in-new-clip-420107404.html|title=David Ross Struggles as 'Bryzzo' Intern in New Clip|work=NBC Chicago|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427125450/http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/david-ross-struggling-in-role-as-bryzzo-intern-in-new-clip-420107404.html|archivedate=April 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Biography}}\n* [[List of Auburn University people]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players with a home run in their final major league at bat]]\n* [[List of Florida Gators baseball players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|David Ross (baseball)|David Ross}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=424325|espn=5206|br=r/rossda01|fangraphs=1551|brm=ross--003dav|retro=R/Prossd001}}\n*{{twitter}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|''Dancing with the Stars'' (US)]] runner up | before= [[James Hinchcliffe]] 